(
<figureCitation id="13082A71FFFCFFEAD1840FC89E44FAA9" box="[159,294,1267,1293]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–34" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1862,1886]" captionTargetBox="[165,1421,181,1838]" captionTargetId="figure-18@12.[165,1421,181,1838]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 27–34. 27–28, dorsal view, scale bar 5.0 mm, 27, Heza sericans Stål, 1859, female, 28, Isocondylus elongatus (Lepeletier &amp; Serville, 1825), male; 29–33, Notocyrtus costai Gil-Santana &amp; Forero, 2009; 29–31, female holotype deposited in MZUSP, 29–30, scale bar 2.0 mm, 29, dorsal view, 30, lateral view, 31, labels and right hind leg glued to a card pinned with the specimen; 32–33, female from French Guiana, dorsal view, 32, scale bar 5.0 mm, 33, head, scale bar 1.0 mm; 34, Notocyrtus depressus Stål, 1872, female, dorsal view, scale bar 5.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6332724" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6332724/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="392">Figs. 29–33</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C329657FFFFCFFEAD18C0E009A26F9D1" pageId="11" pageNumber="392" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="8B8C36F4FFFCFFEAD18C0E009A26F9D1" blockId="11.[151,1437,1339,1833]" pageId="11" pageNumber="392">
<taxonomicName id="4C334D77FFFCFFEAD18C0E009E3CFAF0" authorityName="Gil-Santana &amp; Forero" authorityYear="2009" box="[151,350,1339,1364]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Notocyrtus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="392" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="costai">
<emphasis id="B947EAE6FFFCFFEAD18C0E009E3CFAF0" box="[151,350,1339,1364]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="392">Notocyrtus costai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described based on a single female from 
<collectingCountry id="F3247664FFFCFFEAD2630E009C84FAF1" box="[888,998,1339,1365]" name="Suriname" pageId="11" pageNumber="392">Suriname</collectingCountry>
, currently deposited in MZUSP (
<figureCitation id="13082A71FFFCFFEAD47F0E009F80FADD" captionStart="FIGURES 27–34" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1862,1886]" captionTargetBox="[165,1421,181,1838]" captionTargetId="figure-18@12.[165,1421,181,1838]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 27–34. 27–28, dorsal view, scale bar 5.0 mm, 27, Heza sericans Stål, 1859, female, 28, Isocondylus elongatus (Lepeletier &amp; Serville, 1825), male; 29–33, Notocyrtus costai Gil-Santana &amp; Forero, 2009; 29–31, female holotype deposited in MZUSP, 29–30, scale bar 2.0 mm, 29, dorsal view, 30, lateral view, 31, labels and right hind leg glued to a card pinned with the specimen; 32–33, female from French Guiana, dorsal view, 32, scale bar 5.0 mm, 33, head, scale bar 1.0 mm; 34, Notocyrtus depressus Stål, 1872, female, dorsal view, scale bar 5.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6332724" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6332724/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="392">Figs. 29–31</figureCitation>
). The female examined here (
<figureCitation id="13082A71FFFCFFEAD33D0E649DC3FADD" box="[550,673,1375,1401]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–34" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1862,1886]" captionTargetBox="[165,1421,181,1838]" captionTargetId="figure-18@12.[165,1421,181,1838]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 27–34. 27–28, dorsal view, scale bar 5.0 mm, 27, Heza sericans Stål, 1859, female, 28, Isocondylus elongatus (Lepeletier &amp; Serville, 1825), male; 29–33, Notocyrtus costai Gil-Santana &amp; Forero, 2009; 29–31, female holotype deposited in MZUSP, 29–30, scale bar 2.0 mm, 29, dorsal view, 30, lateral view, 31, labels and right hind leg glued to a card pinned with the specimen; 32–33, female from French Guiana, dorsal view, 32, scale bar 5.0 mm, 33, head, scale bar 1.0 mm; 34, Notocyrtus depressus Stål, 1872, female, dorsal view, scale bar 5.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6332724" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6332724/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="392">Fig. 32–33</figureCitation>
) seems very similar to the 
<typeStatus id="54888856FFFCFFEAD2DC0E649B4EFADD" box="[967,1068,1375,1401]" pageId="11" pageNumber="392">holotype</typeStatus>
, although some small differences in color are recorded: in the postocular portion of the head the large transverse blackish marking is continuous in the specimen from 
<collectingCountry id="F3247664FFFCFFEAD0750E9C9D76FA65" box="[366,532,1447,1473]" name="French Guiana" pageId="11" pageNumber="392">French Guiana</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="13082A71FFFCFFEAD3380E9C9D17FA65" box="[547,629,1447,1473]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–34" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1862,1886]" captionTargetBox="[165,1421,181,1838]" captionTargetId="figure-18@12.[165,1421,181,1838]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 27–34. 27–28, dorsal view, scale bar 5.0 mm, 27, Heza sericans Stål, 1859, female, 28, Isocondylus elongatus (Lepeletier &amp; Serville, 1825), male; 29–33, Notocyrtus costai Gil-Santana &amp; Forero, 2009; 29–31, female holotype deposited in MZUSP, 29–30, scale bar 2.0 mm, 29, dorsal view, 30, lateral view, 31, labels and right hind leg glued to a card pinned with the specimen; 32–33, female from French Guiana, dorsal view, 32, scale bar 5.0 mm, 33, head, scale bar 1.0 mm; 34, Notocyrtus depressus Stål, 1872, female, dorsal view, scale bar 5.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6332724" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6332724/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="392">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
) and it is interrupted at middle in the female 
<typeStatus id="54888856FFFCFFEAD5750E9C9BB1FA65" box="[1134,1235,1447,1473]" pageId="11" pageNumber="392">holotype</typeStatus>
, forming a pair of “large spots in dorsal portion of postocular area” (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA24B05FFFCFFEAD3DF0EF09C9FFA41" author="Gil-Santana, H. R. &amp; Forero, D." box="[708,1021,1483,1509]" pageId="11" pageNumber="392" pagination="55 - 67" refId="ref11926" refString="Gil-Santana, H. R. &amp; Forero, D. (2009) A new species of Notocyrtus, a new synonym of Coilopus, and new records and notes on other Harpactorini (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Reduviidae: Harpactorinae) from South America. Zootaxa, 2148 (1), 55 - 67. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2148.1.5" type="journal article" year="2009">Gil-Santana &amp; Forero 2009</bibRefCitation>
); in the pronotum, the transverse yellow stripe (Gil-Santana &amp; Forero’s “transverse fascia”), between anterior and posterior lobes is somewhat narrower (
<figureCitation id="13082A71FFFCFFEAD1BB0D289F90F989" box="[160,242,1555,1581]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–34" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1862,1886]" captionTargetBox="[165,1421,181,1838]" captionTargetId="figure-18@12.[165,1421,181,1838]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 27–34. 27–28, dorsal view, scale bar 5.0 mm, 27, Heza sericans Stål, 1859, female, 28, Isocondylus elongatus (Lepeletier &amp; Serville, 1825), male; 29–33, Notocyrtus costai Gil-Santana &amp; Forero, 2009; 29–31, female holotype deposited in MZUSP, 29–30, scale bar 2.0 mm, 29, dorsal view, 30, lateral view, 31, labels and right hind leg glued to a card pinned with the specimen; 32–33, female from French Guiana, dorsal view, 32, scale bar 5.0 mm, 33, head, scale bar 1.0 mm; 34, Notocyrtus depressus Stål, 1872, female, dorsal view, scale bar 5.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6332724" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6332724/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="392">Fig. 32</figureCitation>
), and the hind margin of third lobe completely blackish (
<figureCitation id="13082A71FFFCFFEAD27D0D289CD4F989" box="[870,950,1555,1581]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–34" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1862,1886]" captionTargetBox="[165,1421,181,1838]" captionTargetId="figure-18@12.[165,1421,181,1838]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 27–34. 27–28, dorsal view, scale bar 5.0 mm, 27, Heza sericans Stål, 1859, female, 28, Isocondylus elongatus (Lepeletier &amp; Serville, 1825), male; 29–33, Notocyrtus costai Gil-Santana &amp; Forero, 2009; 29–31, female holotype deposited in MZUSP, 29–30, scale bar 2.0 mm, 29, dorsal view, 30, lateral view, 31, labels and right hind leg glued to a card pinned with the specimen; 32–33, female from French Guiana, dorsal view, 32, scale bar 5.0 mm, 33, head, scale bar 1.0 mm; 34, Notocyrtus depressus Stål, 1872, female, dorsal view, scale bar 5.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6332724" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6332724/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="392">Fig. 32</figureCitation>
) (pale yellow in the 
<typeStatus id="54888856FFFCFFEAD5820D289B9CF989" box="[1177,1278,1555,1581]" pageId="11" pageNumber="392">holotype</typeStatus>
, 
<figureCitation id="13082A71FFFCFFEAD4120D289AF3F989" box="[1289,1425,1555,1581]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–34" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1862,1886]" captionTargetBox="[165,1421,181,1838]" captionTargetId="figure-18@12.[165,1421,181,1838]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 27–34. 27–28, dorsal view, scale bar 5.0 mm, 27, Heza sericans Stål, 1859, female, 28, Isocondylus elongatus (Lepeletier &amp; Serville, 1825), male; 29–33, Notocyrtus costai Gil-Santana &amp; Forero, 2009; 29–31, female holotype deposited in MZUSP, 29–30, scale bar 2.0 mm, 29, dorsal view, 30, lateral view, 31, labels and right hind leg glued to a card pinned with the specimen; 32–33, female from French Guiana, dorsal view, 32, scale bar 5.0 mm, 33, head, scale bar 1.0 mm; 34, Notocyrtus depressus Stål, 1872, female, dorsal view, scale bar 5.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6332724" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6332724/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="392">Figs. 29–30</figureCitation>
). Additionally, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA24B05FFFCFFEAD0290D0C9D18F9F5" author="Gil-Santana, H. R. &amp; Forero, D." box="[306,634,1591,1617]" pageId="11" pageNumber="392" pagination="55 - 67" refId="ref11926" refString="Gil-Santana, H. R. &amp; Forero, D. (2009) A new species of Notocyrtus, a new synonym of Coilopus, and new records and notes on other Harpactorini (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Reduviidae: Harpactorinae) from South America. Zootaxa, 2148 (1), 55 - 67. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2148.1.5" type="journal article" year="2009">Gil-Santana &amp; Forero (2009)</bibRefCitation>
recorded the total length of the female 
<typeStatus id="54888856FFFCFFEAD5210D0C9BFEF9F5" box="[1082,1180,1591,1617]" pageId="11" pageNumber="392">holotype</typeStatus>
11.0 / 13.0 mm, while the female from 
<collectingCountry id="F3247664FFFCFFEAD04A0D609E95F9D1" box="[337,503,1627,1653]" name="French Guiana" pageId="11" pageNumber="392">French Guiana</collectingCountry>
measured 9.5 / 
<quantity id="4CCB9B11FFFCFFEAD3B20D619C6FF9D1" box="[681,781,1626,1653]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.25" pageId="11" pageNumber="392" unit="mm" value="12.5">12.5 mm</quantity>
to the tip of abdomen and hemelytra, respectively.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
